00:20:31,940 --> 00:20:34,090
parts which are most
helpful, and you know,

534
00:20:34,090 --> 00:20:37,110
because you actually
already helped them.

535
00:20:37,110 --> 00:20:39,860
It's like you had an office
hour where everyone attended,

536
00:20:39,860 --> 00:20:42,030
and now you get to
explain the answer, right?

537
00:20:42,030 --> 00:20:46,380
And so that's been
really exciting for us.

538
00:20:46,380 --> 00:20:50,180
So those are some of the active
learning benefits we found.

539
00:20:50,180 --> 00:20:52,415
And then in terms
of technology, there

540
00:20:52,415 --> 00:20:54,280
are I guess three ways
for using technology

541
00:20:54,280 --> 00:20:55,490
to enhance the class.

542
00:20:55,490 --> 00:20:57,440
The reading questions
as Jerry said,

543
00:20:57,440 --> 00:20:59,910
these are, by and large,
a way to get students

544
00:20:59,910 --> 00:21:03,005
to at least open the PDF
that has the reading.

545
00:21:03,005 --> 00:21:05,980
The students at MIT are going
to play some game theory

546
00:21:05,980 --> 00:21:08,660
and manage their time to
balance a lot of obligations.

547
00:21:08,660 --> 00:21:12,779

548
00:21:12,779 --> 00:21:14,570
You can't expect them
to say your course is

549
00:21:14,570 --> 00:21:16,403
the most important
course, and of course I'm

550
00:21:16,403 --> 00:21:18,300
going to do this before
I do anything else.

551
00:21:18,300 --> 00:21:20,140
But at least if they
get to the stage

552
00:21:20,140 --> 00:21:21,600
where they open that
document, because they

553
00:21:21,600 --> 00:21:23,620
know they're going to get
graded, 5% of the grade

554
00:21:23,620 --> 00:21:24,800
on answering these
reading questions,

555
00:21:24,800 --> 00:21:26,620
you have a good
chance that they're

556
00:21:26,620 --> 00:21:28,259
going to have some
first exposure.

557
00:21:28,259 --> 00:21:30,800
And if you create an expectation
at the beginning of the term

558
00:21:30,800 --> 00:21:33,175
that we're going to assume
that they've done the reading,

559
00:21:33,175 --> 00:21:35,640
and not go over it as if
they didn't, then that also

560
00:21:35,640 --> 00:21:38,570
helps to enforce and get
students to actually do it.

561
00:21:38,570 --> 00:21:41,129
So they are actually
graded on these questions

562
00:21:41,129 --> 00:21:42,920
in terms of whether
they're right or wrong,

563
00:21:42,920 --> 00:21:45,070
and they're not meant to be
particularly hard questions.

564
00:21:45,070 --> 00:21:46,903
They're more like
questions that are exactly

565
00:21:46,903 --> 00:21:48,592
parallel to an example,
so at least they

566
00:21:48,592 --> 00:21:50,800
have to look through the
example, change the numbers,

567
00:21:50,800 --> 00:21:52,620
plug-in an answer.

568
00:21:52,620 --> 00:21:55,087
Clickers and attendance.

569
00:21:55,087 --> 00:21:56,670
When you do an active
learning course,

